<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-01-05T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-01-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="141" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d141">
                                <note rend="inline" type="source">Roosevelt Papers</note>
                                <head>
                                    <hi rend="italic">The Coordinator of Information</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Donovan</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">President</gloss>
                                    </hi>
                                </head>
                                <opener>
                                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-01-05">January 5,
                                            1942</date>.</dateline>
                                </opener>
                                <p rend="center"><hi rend="smallcaps">Memorandum for the
                                        President</hi></p>
                                <p>No. 129. The following is a copy of a cablegram which I have just
                                    received from our representative in Cairo: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                        <p>“For Donovan only. Do not repeat until you hear from the
                                            President. Plans are being discussed here for French
                                            North Africa, involving every phase of propaganda
                                            needing printing and radio equipment in large
                                            quantities, also extensive carefully-selected personnel
                                            and organization, as anything British is poison to the
                                            French. This <pb facs="0330" n="256" xml:id="pg_256"/>
                                            effort will have to be strictly an American one, as
                                            written reports on the way show British technical
                                            equipment to be very scarce. Will you cable details as
                                            available, so we can inform people here of our ability
                                            to meet requirements. You in Washington will know
                                            immediately whether recommendations and general plans
                                            being forwarded to the President are rejected or
                                            accepted.”</p>
                                    </quote></p>
                            </div>
                            </body></text></TEI>